    <div class="section firstReview">
      

<div id="review_1951874102" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1951874102" />
    <a title="Emma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28602001-emma"><img alt="Emma" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1438967931p2/28602001.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1951874102?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emma" href="/user/show/28602001-emma">Emma</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/32334413-feast-of-sorrow">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/28602001-emma?shelf=netgalley">netgalley</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1951874102" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4786468839272550463">This was a feast indeed, a rare treat of a novel so richly evocative that the reader cannot help but lose themselves in the wonder of arriving in ancient Rome. <br/><br/>Set around the household of Marcus Gavius Apicius, a wealthy Roman gourmet who probably lived during the reign of Tiberius (1st Century AD), it is told through the eyes of his coquus Thrasius. While the personal and familial elements of the novel are pure invention, it is clear that King has researched the contemporary and/or primary sour</span>
  <span id="freeText4786468839272550463" style="display:none">This was a feast indeed, a rare treat of a novel so richly evocative that the reader cannot help but lose themselves in the wonder of arriving in ancient Rome. <br /><br />Set around the household of Marcus Gavius Apicius, a wealthy Roman gourmet who probably lived during the reign of Tiberius (1st Century AD), it is told through the eyes of his coquus Thrasius. While the personal and familial elements of the novel are pure invention, it is clear that King has researched the contemporary and/or primary sources for the larger structures of the narrative, including the high politics of Rome, especially the rise and fall of personalities such as Livia, Sejanus, Apicata, Claudius, and Pliny amongst others. As with the best history, the sources provide the foundation for the building of an argument and King has used the same methodology to present us with a fascinating experience, a unique way into these lives: food. The detail is extraordinary, with original recipes, cooking techniques, feasting, and the intricate details of running a patrician's kitchen. It's not just for foodies though, as with the best dishes, each part is perfectly balanced; never too much detail, just enough to illuminate and tantalise rather than overwhelm. I loved it all.<br /><br />Well, almost all. I can't get the rather horrible thought of eating a pig's vulva out of my mind. <br /><br />ARC via Netgalley.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4786468839272550463" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


