    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1985425954" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1985425954" />
    <a title="Emily" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2431873-emily"><img alt="Emily" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1477433724p2/2431873.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1985425954?book_show_action=true">Oct 18, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emily" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emily" href="/user/show/2431873-emily">Emily</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2431873-emily?shelf=food">food</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2431873-emily?shelf=antiquity">antiquity</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2431873-emily?shelf=rome">rome</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1985425954" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5363127592452629841">This took me over a month (!) to read, which is insane because it features two of my favorite things: Rome and food. While I thoroughly enjoyed the descriptions of the meals and the author clearly did her research, I found the characters and plot pretty boring. <br/><br/>This book centers around Thrasius, the <i>coquus</i> (or chef) for Marcus Gavius Apicius, one of the richest men in Rome and a notable gourmand. The issue is that it covers the entirety of Thrasius&apos;s life, which means each chapter is more of a v</span>
  <span id="freeText5363127592452629841" style="display:none">This took me over a month (!) to read, which is insane because it features two of my favorite things: Rome and food. While I thoroughly enjoyed the descriptions of the meals and the author clearly did her research, I found the characters and plot pretty boring. <br /><br />This book centers around Thrasius, the <i>coquus</i> (or chef) for Marcus Gavius Apicius, one of the richest men in Rome and a notable gourmand. The issue is that it covers the entirety of Thrasius's life, which means each chapter is more of a vignette of a particular period than an addition to a cohesive story. In the first part of the book, Thrasius has a potentially deadly and antagonistic relationship with Apicius's mother, Popilla - then she dies. He falls in love with another slave, Passia, who doesn't return his affections at first - then she does. Apicius wants to start a cooking school, which is a silly idea - until it isn't! It wasn't that any of this was particularly bad. I was just never compelled to read on, so I kept leaving this book at home when going on trips and forgetting that it existed. Which is too bad, because it's also full of gems like:<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>Peacock meatballs rank in the first place, provided they are fried until they burst their skins. Pheasant meatballs rank in the second place, then rabbit third, then chicken fourth, and tender young pork ones are fifth.</i>
</blockquote><br />What a take!! (That's straight from the surviving recipes of Apicius.) There are also lavishly described dinner parties where the attendees busy themselves eating dormice (they are eating dormice LITERALLY ALL THE TIME) and anything flavored with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silphium" target="_new" rel="nofollow noopener">silphium</a>, a classical herb that has since gone extinct. I liked the book best when it bordered on the ridiculous. I burst out laughing when I got to "Pliny, you must try the flamingo tongues--they are the most superb flavor!" <br /><br />That's another problem with this book, though. The author falls into the trap that so many historical fiction authors do, where their main characters intersect too heavily with the known history of the imperial reign at the time. There's an over-convoluted relationship between Apicius and Sejanus, and it's Thrasius who contributes heavily to Sejanus's downfall. Thrasius is present for too many meetings between Apicius and peers for no discernible reason. This may be personal preference, but I would have enjoyed a tighter, more time-bound story about Thrasius that set him in the correct era, but didn't have him rubbing shoulders with Livia and Tiberius every 20 pages. I'm interested in the food, not another edition of "Livia killed everyone!!"<br /><br />Some other thoughts: <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br /><br />- Popilla's death was ridiculous! It seemed like a contrived way to introduce the concept of <i>paterfamilias</i>. It's another example of writing the story to fit your historical research, rather than writing a story that fits into the time period.<br /><br />- Thrasius turns out to be kind of an asshole. He develops this all-abiding holier-than-thou stance on how quickly Apicius spends money, but there's no real reason for him to do so. It's not until the end of the book that you realize just how fast Apicius is spending. If that had come up earlier, it might have made sense. Instead, Thrasius just wanders around complaining about how much of a spendthrift Apicius is. Not a fun guy to have at a party. I also couldn't believe that he almost told Sotas about the ruse at the Fides ceremony at the end of the book. You're going to invalidate this dude's entire life?? So selfish.<br /><br />- The entire plotline with Sejanus, Apicius, and Apicata was so overblown and silly. I feel like Roman fiction authors also over-strive for Dark and Sexy plotlines, and they never quite work out. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />It's hard to wholeheartedly recommend this book, but some of my other friends enjoyed it more than me. If you like Rome and food, it's worth trying out - even if you end up just flipping through the chapter headings to read the recipe excerpts.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5363127592452629841" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


