<div id="review_1729168264" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1729168264" />
    <a title="Jessica Strawser" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/58465020-jessica-strawser"><img alt="Jessica Strawser" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1476975331p2/58465020.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1729168264?book_show_action=true">Dec 29, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jessica Strawser" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jessica Strawser" href="/user/show/58465020-jessica-strawser">Jessica Strawser</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1729168264" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13885531539070564503">I&apos;ve always been fascinated by ancient Rome, and thought I had a decent grip on its history from other books, TV programs and visiting the city firsthand, but Crystal King&apos;s Feast of Sorrow schooled me in the best possible way -- which is to say the story swept me away to another time, another world. The author&apos;s meticulous research is evident from Page 1, but it&apos;s the characters who carry the story and offer us a fascinating glimpse into the complex relationships forged within and even across t</span>
  <span id="freeText13885531539070564503" style="display:none">I've always been fascinated by ancient Rome, and thought I had a decent grip on its history from other books, TV programs and visiting the city firsthand, but Crystal King's Feast of Sorrow schooled me in the best possible way -- which is to say the story swept me away to another time, another world. The author's meticulous research is evident from Page 1, but it's the characters who carry the story and offer us a fascinating glimpse into the complex relationships forged within and even across the classes during that time (particularly at extremes--the wealthy and the slaves), and the beliefs and customs (and, yes, tragedies) that made up everyday life under the watchful eyes of the gods.<br /><br />What makes the story delightfully unique is that we see all of this through and around food -- and its early days as not mere sustenance but pure pleasure, experimentation, celebration and a symbol of status. Some of the earliest "foodies," as it turns out, essentially took credit for the work of the talented chefs they enslaved. After all, they owned all that was produced in their kitchens. This is a story of innovation and exploitation, loyalty and love, rivalry and roots. Highly recommend for fans of historical fiction and/or cuisine (and seriously, if you're into both, you're in for a treat). (Many thanks to the author and publisher for the opportunity to read and review early.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="13885531539070564503" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


