    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2340660820" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2340660820" />
    <a title="Jenna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3536004-jenna"><img alt="Jenna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1535136437p2/3536004.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2340660820?book_show_action=true">Mar 30, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jenna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jenna" href="/user/show/3536004-jenna">Jenna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3536004-jenna?shelf=historical-fic">historical-fic</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2340660820" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7093926895533647897">In this beautifully-written debut novel, Crystal King brings to life the world of ancient Rome. She has masterfully created a brilliant story centered around the oldest known collections of recipes and Apicius, the only well-known gourmand from ancient Rome. <br/>Narrating Feast of Sorrow is Thrasius, Apicius&apos; fictional slave and coquus (chef). Through his eyes, Rome of the 1st century is brought to stunning life, the opulence and violence, the treachery and treason. Through Thrasius&apos; eyes, we watch </span>
  <span id="freeText7093926895533647897" style="display:none">In this beautifully-written debut novel, Crystal King brings to life the world of ancient Rome. She has masterfully created a brilliant story centered around the oldest known collections of recipes and Apicius, the only well-known gourmand from ancient Rome. <br />Narrating Feast of Sorrow is Thrasius, Apicius' fictional slave and coquus (chef). Through his eyes, Rome of the 1st century is brought to stunning life, the opulence and violence, the treachery and treason. Through Thrasius' eyes, we watch as Apicius' obsession with obtaining a post as gastronomic advisor to Caesar and his vulgar displays of wealth nearly bring his family to ruin. Thrasius remains a loyal slave and then friend throughout, always assisting and advising, and of course, preparing the decadent dishes with which Apicius so impressed the wealthy of Rome. <br />There is more, so much more! A review cannot possibly suffice; one must read this incredible novel for oneself! My only complaint is that most of the characters were portrayed as literate which I believe is untrue for Rome of that time. Aside from this detail though, I found Ms. King's portrayal to be believable and beautiful and real. What Mary Renault did in bringing to life ancient Greece, Crystal King has done in bringing to life ancient Rome in Feast of Sorrow. I look forward to reading more of her books in the future.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7093926895533647897" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

