    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1901209109" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1901209109" />
    <a title="Kara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1288287-kara"><img alt="Kara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1227469207p2/1288287.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1901209109?book_show_action=true">May 25, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kara" href="/user/show/1288287-kara">Kara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1288287-kara?shelf=history-food">history-food</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1288287-kara?shelf=history-ancient">history-ancient</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1288287-kara?shelf=food-and-drink">food-and-drink</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1288287-kara?shelf=rome">rome</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1901209109" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16289060408318528248"><br/>There is great attention to detail here as well a good sense of the sprawling big picture of the Roman Empire, and both the day to day facts and larger than life people and historical events are slipped in more or less organically without a lot of shoehorning. The author did her research, and presents a magnificent portrait of the Julio-Claudian dynasty through the lens of the famed Apicius and his not-so famed cook, who gave him that fame, literally, on a silver platter.<br/><br/>I just wish there had be</span>
  <span id="freeText16289060408318528248" style="display:none"><br />There is great attention to detail here as well a good sense of the sprawling big picture of the Roman Empire, and both the day to day facts and larger than life people and historical events are slipped in more or less organically without a lot of shoehorning. The author did her research, and presents a magnificent portrait of the Julio-Claudian dynasty through the lens of the famed Apicius and his not-so famed cook, who gave him that fame, literally, on a silver platter.<br /><br />I just wish there had been more focus on the <i>food</i>.<br /><br />There is so much time spent on the politics and factions and who’s-married-to-who and who’s-sleeping-with-who drama, that at times the feast we were promised is pushed something to the background. I wanted the food to be center stage, not just part of the scenery!<br /><br />I was expecting more of a below-decks-story with the chef and other denizens of the kitchen as main characters and the story focused entirely on serving up the best gods damned feasts ever, with so much attention on making the perfect dormouse in honey that it would be something of an afterthought to the main characters and the reader that the food was being whisked away to be eaten by Augustus or Livia or Ovid or Sejanus or any of the many other famous people the poor cook keeps getting thrust in the way of. Sigh. What could have been.<br /><br />It’s so ridiculous that this poor slave gets a front row seat to major events and players of the time that even he is outright wondering: ‘Wait. What? What am I doing here? Why am I not in my kitchen again?’<br /><br />Meanwhile, I hope we weren’t meant to like Apicius, because he is all over the place, as unpredictable as a tornado, leaving all the other characters unsure if he is going to randomly start handing out Falernian wine or deaths sentences to those around him. <br /><br />And speaking of death – this story got a lot more dark than I expected. I advise the reader not to get too attached to any particular character, because the death toll mounts up quite a bit by the end. <br /><br />Of course it’s important to not put on rose colored glasses about the time period and remember that Slavery, Dictatorship, and Lack-Of-Basic-Civil-Liberties-For-Everyone Is Bad, but wow, that got really dark at certain points.<br /><br />The overall story was good – but definitely not the meal I ordered!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16289060408318528248" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

