    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1756252775" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1756252775" />
    <a title="Lynn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2064321-lynn"><img alt="Lynn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1472840786p2/2064321.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1756252775?book_show_action=true">Sep 12, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lynn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lynn" href="/user/show/2064321-lynn">Lynn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1756252775" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9983211206345868408">Crystal King is a fellow Debutante Ball author, and lucky for me, I had the chance to read an advanced version of this novel.<br/><br/>Apicius, Apicius, Apicius. What a character. He is deplorable at times, and yet somehow I finished Feast of Sorrow with a softness for him. In other words, King has done a tremendous job of building him as a complete and complicated character with all of his humanity - beauty and faults alike. In fact, that was my favorite part of this novel: the depth of the characterizat</span>
  <span id="freeText9983211206345868408" style="display:none">Crystal King is a fellow Debutante Ball author, and lucky for me, I had the chance to read an advanced version of this novel.<br /><br />Apicius, Apicius, Apicius. What a character. He is deplorable at times, and yet somehow I finished Feast of Sorrow with a softness for him. In other words, King has done a tremendous job of building him as a complete and complicated character with all of his humanity - beauty and faults alike. In fact, that was my favorite part of this novel: the depth of the characterization for each of the people depicted. Their varied personalities and relationships were what drew me into this world of ancient Rome, and I devoured this story quickly, completely immersed in the these characters' often painful but always rich lives.<br /><br />I stayed up much past my bed time to finish Feast of Sorrow, and then when I did, my head was spinning with so many emotions and reactions it was impossible to bring myself back from Rome. (Is there a better reason to be exhausted?) So be forewarned, the ending is a doozy! <br /><br />Normally I wouldn't think to pick up historical fiction, but I loved this novel so much I was sad to turn the last pages. King has whetted my appetite for this genre (ha! - see what I did there?), and I certainly hope in the future I have the privilege of reading much more from her.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9983211206345868408" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


